text: John 6:46 says â€œnot that anyone has seen the Father except he who is from God; he has seen the Father.â€ And 1 Timothy 6:14-16 says, â€œto keep the commandment unstained and free from reproach until the appearing of our Lord Jesus Christ, which he will display at the proper timeâ€”he who is the blessed and only Sovereign, the King of kings and Lord of lords,Â who alone has immortality, who dwells in unapproachable light, whom no one has ever seen or can seeâ€¦â€  Tell me, please, how it is that William Paul Young thought it would be Biblically sound to portray a physical representation of God the Father given the above Biblical testimony? And this is just one of the many Theological errors found in Mr. Young's book. He says, in his book, that God the Father suffered on the cross by showing scars in His hands; this is heresy called Patripassionism. It was Jesus, God the Son, who suffered on the Cross, not the Father. Another is Jesus saying, "I am the best way any human can relate to Papa [the Father] or Sarayu [the Holy Spirit]. To see me is to see them." No, He isn't, "the best way." He is the only way. Period.  I don't expect this little excerpt to change anyone's mind. There have been many sermons, articles, podcasts, and even books written by very intelligent pastors and theologians like Albert Mohler and John Piper condemning the egregious errors in this book; but please have some discernment while you consume this kind of material.

text: I had an opportunity to attend a screening in Thousand Oaks, CA last week. Here's the deal - this film is a game-changer. Just like the book, your view of God will be altered. Is it possible that He loves us that much? Octavia Spencer is stunning, but the surprise for me was the performance of Aviv Alush. I was incredibly moved by his authentic portrayal of Jesus. Apparently, he's a star in Israel, but I'm fairly certain he's about to be famous here in the U.S. Get ready, folks. This film is nothing short of spectacular. text: Youngâ€™s stereotypical characterization of the Father as a â€œlarge beaming African-American woman,â€ the Son as a Jew with a large nose, and the Holy Spirit as a mysterious Asian female3 makes me more than a little queasy. Furthermore, virtually every theological heresy begins with a misconception of the nature of God. The Shack is no exception. After chiding those he believes to have misconceptions about the Trinity, Young proceeds to compromise, confuse, or outright contradict biblical orthodoxy. He pictures the Father bearing crucifixion scars as well as being incarnated in tandem with the Holy Spirit. In historic, biblical Christianity only the Son is incarnated and only the Son suffers and dies on the cross. Moreover, Young pontificates that Jesus â€œhas never drawn upon his nature as God to do anythingâ€ (emphasis in original). Those who have read through the Bible will immediately recognize the falsity of this statementâ€”particularly with respect to the resurrection. For example, in Johnâ€™s Gospel Jesus says, â€œThe reason my Father loves me is that I lay down my lifeâ€”only to take it up again. No one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord. I have authority to lay it down and authority to take it up again. This command I received from my Fatherâ€ (John 10:17â€“18 NIV). Equally problematic is the fact that Young negates the notion of functional subordination within the Godhead. As the large beaming African-American woman in Youngâ€™s novel explains, the Trinity is â€œin a circle of relationship, not a chain of Command.â€¦Hierarchy would make no sense among usâ€ (emphasis in original). In biblical orthodoxy, however, the incarnate Christ says, â€œI tell you the truth, the Son can do nothing by himself; He can do only what He sees his Father doing, because whatever the Father does the Son also doesâ€ (John 5:19 NIV). Put another way, functional hierarchy is not antithetical to ontological equality. Finally, Young has Jesusâ€”the Jew with the big noseâ€”declaring, â€œIâ€™m not a Christianâ€ and â€œI have no desire to make them [Buddhists, Mormons, Muslims, etc.) Christian.â€ Indeed, Young describes Christians as religious fanatics and part of a sinful world system. In sharp distinction, the followers of Christ adopted the word â€œChristianâ€ in the midst of suffering and persecution. The apostle Peter, for example, writes, â€œIf you suffer as a Christian, do not be ashamed but praise God that you bear that nameâ€ (1 Pet. 4:16 NIV; cf. Acts 11:26). The fact that The Shack is being touted by those who take the sacred name of Christ upon their lips is a sad commentary on Christian discernment. As has been well said, â€œIf you havenâ€™t read The Shack, donâ€™t.â€ â€”Hank Hanegraaff Hank Hanegraaff is host of the Bible Answer Man broadcast heard daily throughout the United States and Canada. text: Beware of "The Shack" movie: William P. Young's best selling book The Shack is considered by many solid Bible-based ministries to contain New Age teachings, and even occult overtones. The movie is probably worse since images can be very powerful. If by any chance you think this is a Christian movie, it is not!!! The book and movie contain Universalist teachings. The story embraces the false doctrine of universal Reconciliation. The character travels to the shack and finds it renovated into a beautiful cottage with three persons in residence: a breezy, cheery African-American woman who likes to cook and who gives her name as Elousia; Jesus, a short Middle-Eastern man always at work in a shed; and an Asian looking woman named Sarayu who is "keeper of the gardens." Mack soon learns that Elousia is Papa -- God the Father -- and Sarayu is the Holy Spirit. Jesus is, of course, Jesus. I believe it is heretic, deceiving and dangerous to immature Christians or anyone, for that matter. 1 Tim. 4:1-2

text: I love coming here to read ALL the comments posted about "The Shack" book and movie...both comments that praise and those that condemn because it really gives me insight into the mindset of my fellow members of mankind.  Let me ask you this: If we were all together in a room with Jesus or whomever you believe in or have faith in as being The Almighty or Creator of ALL,  Author of the Universe, Shepherd that guides you...whatever...what would be more likely to bring a smile to HIS, HER or IT's "face" or spiritual essence? All the bickering and fault finding and "imperfections" and alleged biblical "inaccuracies"  and how it "falls short" of Christian or other religious beliefs... stated about this book and/or movie or the slinging of insults at each other or disrespect for other's religions or beliefs..and even some Pastors and Ministers -supposed religious people who are supposed to guide their flocks denouncing it....or would a smile be elicited by those who have the heart and spiritual awareness to SEE and appreciate the virtues that the book and movie are truly about: Love, Goodness, Forgiveness, Compassion, Non-Judgement, Good Relationships and the same people who share this with their loved ones, neighbors and even total strangers?   NOBODY on this Earth, past present or future has the right to claim to "Know It All' about Who or What God is or isn't nor state that THEIR religion is the one and only way to salvation or Heaven or a better place or state of being or to tell people they should not read this book or see the movie for this. that or some other reason. Furthermore, to conclude that the book's author is trying to tell us or have us believe that God is a woman and black show that such conclusions demonstrate that the whole point of why God is portrayed as a black woman was missed. It's just a M O V I E based upon one book written by one dad for his children. It expresses his thoughts and feelings and opinions to which he is entitled. If the book and/or movie made you feel good or inspired you or rekindled your love in some way shape or form then THAT is all that matters....and if it did...GOOD for YOU.
author: gamecopiestr8

text: Expand your world and allow the possibilities to come to you.  I have not read the book or seen this movie but will now as I am interested in trying to understand why people would turn away from anything that does not agree with their beliefs.    We have minds that allow us to be critical thinkers and creatures.  If someone disagrees with anything so quickly because it is different than them, then we all lose.  To me, this seems to be rooted in a fear bases view of faith.   If you do not see or feel God's presence in everything and everyone around you, then the true message of Christ is lost.  We are so small in the landscape of life so if someone thinks they know it all and the truth is only one way, you don't understand true love and compassion.  Hatred of any kind how no place in people who say they beliee in God or   Movies challenge us, entertain us and expand our world.  It allows us to enter intelligent conversation to wonder, question and deepen our own beliefs.  If we assume we know it all then our ego is getting in the way.  Even Catholic priests question and struggle with many concepts in the bible.  Take from it what feeds your soul and leave the rest.  To criticize the movie and anyone who may believe that God could be a woman sheds light on deeper issues with such limited thinking.  Humans have been debated and fought over interpretations of the bible for centuries.  Where has it gotten us?  We have become less tolerant and small minded.   Model the love your faith teaches.  Christ was a rebel, embrace that.   Others scorned and even killed people who were different; Christ showed love and compassion and said that was not the way.  Loosen up the gripe that is so tightly squeezing out the true message of Christ.  I promise you will be happier and healthier to follow the examples of a loving God.

text: 7-10-17  I've never wrote a Journal before. To think of my writing is humerus. For I'm dialysis. As I think to myself what is a point? Who would care of my voice in their ears? But laying next to my wife I realize maybe one day kids and wife would be a beneficial.   As laying next to my half. My mind slip away.......Have you ever wonder who god is? Have you ever stop and listen or even dare to question our creator? I don't know about every one. But I know I have. Some time I wish its as easy to write a letter to god. But if it where that easy. Then the question of life wouldn't be so complicated. We know we all think we focuses on god. We all reminds ourself and love ones. "We love god". But putting my foot out in the working world as my 1st truly honest business man. Starting from his humble start. In trailer and truck. With his last money he went back to construction. A busy humble small success. "I realized". I've forgotten about god. This long road path. With every step of the way some how I felt he is with me. All this I tell me self each time I see a penny on my road path. Reminding my self two word..."thank god for walking with me".  For tomorrow that meal for my family might be gone.  For the next 16 years with my wife. Some how we never starve. We manage to make day by day. With little improve each year. The rodeo was complicated and strive thought extreme complication. But who house is beautiful?  I look on FB, instagrame, every one house is beautiful happy like a dream. The wonderful 1000 friends or followers, The amazing party and event, the beautiful girlfriend, that crazy drugs life. That sexy outfit, forcing our eyes on the color, fabrics of life on medias. But I have forget to thank god.   It's take months of busy working. Focusing on the next step in life. It come down to one movie today that help me stop. And write this self journal. "The shack"...the movies help me truly understand "who god is". Thank you for giving me that touch of god again.

text: There's a scene in this film where the character of Octavia Spencer (God) told the main character the words, "And you have no idea how much I love you." Now, I know this line has been said before in other films and was delivered in a more emotional way, but this is the only time I cry hearing it. You see, I was never a religious person. Religion and I just don't get along. But I do believe in God. I do believe that there is greater being out there watching everything unfold. Seeing everyone as they should be seen, equals, like sons and daughters a parent unconditionally and equally loves. When octavia delivered that line, it touched something inside me. It felt almost like a hug, a rub on the back or a squeeze while holding my  hand. And she wasn't even looking directly to the camera. Like I said, I'm not a religious person and I'm still not even after this film. But what this film did is that it reminded me that I am one of God's sons. That I will always be loved despite my sins, imperfections, and failures. And more importantly that everyone else is my brother and sister and maybe the best way for me to know how much God loves me is to love His/Her other children.

text: I remember being at one of my lowest points in life about 10 years ago. I had grown up in abusive foster/adoptive homes, and my little sister was kidnapped when I was 8. My entire childhood I blamed myself for not protecting her after I had promised my birth mum I would always be there for her.  I was adopted by a pastoral family a few years later and one day my youth pastor took me aside and gave me The Shack to read, not promising anything, just hoping I wasn't going to make a bad choice with my life. I couldn't put it down that night. I read through it and poured myself into the pages. The next morning I remember my parents asking me what had happened, what was this change they had seen over night. Now my dad is a traditional pastor; he's got no time for fantasies, just his work with God. I passed him the book and challenged him to read it. He went out a few days later and but over 100 copies to take with him on his missions trips. This is who I had always seen God as, and I saw my family completely change their views on faith because of a great author's insight to Grace. I still read the chapter "Bring on the Judge" as part of my devotions
